WEBVTT

00:06.876 --> 00:07.224
.

00:07.268 --> 00:09.009
- [sighs]

00:09.052 --> 00:11.663
- Ready to get started?

00:11.707 --> 00:12.882
- Yeah.

00:12.925 --> 00:15.841
[soft piano music]

00:15.885 --> 00:23.023
♪

00:55.359 --> 00:57.100
- Okay, thank you.

00:57.144 --> 00:58.232
Let's step on the scale,
please.

00:58.275 --> 01:05.152
♪

01:28.784 --> 01:32.222
You've got a lot of history
and biology to overcome.

01:32.266 --> 01:33.789
Your ghrelin is out of whack,

01:33.832 --> 01:35.921
and you've got
high leptin resistance

01:35.965 --> 01:38.402
making you feel hungrier
than you actually are.

01:38.446 --> 01:40.187
But then your body is terrible
at signaling

01:40.230 --> 01:41.710
when you're truly full.

01:41.753 --> 01:43.233
Add to that
all the emotional stuff

01:43.277 --> 01:44.539
you're working through,

01:44.582 --> 01:46.236
having a healthy relationship
with food

01:46.280 --> 01:48.369
will be a lifelong battle
for you.

01:48.412 --> 01:51.546
- Well, then it's a good thing
I'm halfway done, right?

01:51.589 --> 01:52.677
[chuckles]

01:52.721 --> 01:54.418
- You'll need someone
to work with you

01:54.462 --> 01:56.942
on your ingrained
emotional assignments to food.

01:56.986 --> 01:58.074
- No, no, no.

01:58.118 --> 02:00.250
No, I really like going
to group.

02:00.294 --> 02:01.686
It's great.
I share in there.

02:01.730 --> 02:03.123
Everyone's really supportive--
- Iggy.

02:03.166 --> 02:04.428
You haven't logged in once.

02:04.472 --> 02:06.169
- No, that's not true.
I've--

02:06.213 --> 02:09.520
- The system keeps track.

02:09.564 --> 02:13.263
You have to stop lying
and do the work.

02:13.307 --> 02:15.135
There's someone I want you
to talk to.

02:18.181 --> 02:21.445
- It's a recovery coach?

02:21.489 --> 02:23.491
What is that, a food monitor?
Food chaperone?

02:23.534 --> 02:26.146
That's not happening.
No, absolutely not.

02:27.843 --> 02:29.149
No.

02:29.192 --> 02:32.108
[solemn music]

02:32.152 --> 02:34.110
♪

02:34.154 --> 02:35.677
Can I put my pants on now,
please?

02:41.030 --> 02:42.205
- Dr. Goodwin.
- Yeah?

02:42.249 --> 02:43.467
- Dr. Goodwin.
- Yes, Dr. Kao, what's up?

02:43.511 --> 02:44.773
You caught me.
- I just wanted to check

02:44.816 --> 02:46.166
and see, not to rush you.
- Mm-hmm, okay.

02:46.209 --> 02:47.471
- But I was just curious.
- Yeah.

02:47.515 --> 02:49.212
- How are the interviews going?
- Interviews.

02:49.256 --> 02:50.735
- For the interim chair
of neurology.

02:50.779 --> 02:52.650
- Yes, those interviews
are going great.

02:52.694 --> 02:53.912
Really good.

02:53.956 --> 02:55.305
- You haven't started them yet,
have you?

02:55.349 --> 02:56.741
- Not in the technical sense,
no, but Agnes,

02:56.785 --> 02:59.309
you are the best interim,
interim chair of neurology

02:59.353 --> 03:00.876
a medical director could
ask for.

03:00.919 --> 03:02.486
- I appreciate your confidence
in me,

03:02.530 --> 03:04.662
but Dr. Kapoor is a 30-year
veteran in the field,

03:04.706 --> 03:06.229
and I'm not even an attending.

03:06.273 --> 03:08.057
I am woefully underprepared.

03:08.100 --> 03:09.406
- You're not, Dr. Kao,

03:09.450 --> 03:10.625
but if it makes you
feel better,

03:10.668 --> 03:12.279
I will start
those interviews today.

03:12.322 --> 03:13.845
- Ah, Max, we've got a problem.

03:13.889 --> 03:15.630
- Tomorrow,
but what's one more day?

03:15.673 --> 03:16.892
How can I help?
- Sorry, Agnes.

03:16.935 --> 03:18.502
No, Max--
- This way, yep.

03:18.546 --> 03:21.157
- Our blood bank supplies have
reached critical lows.

03:21.201 --> 03:22.550
- How did that happen?

03:22.593 --> 03:24.029
- I've narrowed it down
to vampires

03:24.073 --> 03:25.205
or the global pandemic.

03:25.248 --> 03:26.510
- There's a nicer way
to say that.

03:26.554 --> 03:28.251
- A third of our blood
donations normally come

03:28.295 --> 03:30.514
from high school
or business blood drives,

03:30.558 --> 03:31.689
but with everyone at home--

03:31.733 --> 03:33.169
- Well, what about
hospital employees?

03:33.213 --> 03:34.692
- Tapped out.

03:34.736 --> 03:36.259
Everyone's within their
eight-week turnaround window.

03:36.303 --> 03:38.261
- But we've got
backup supplies, right?

03:38.305 --> 03:39.871
- Um...

03:39.915 --> 03:42.396
most of it went
toward Haven yesterday.

03:42.439 --> 03:44.702
There was a ten-car pileup
on the BQE.

03:44.746 --> 03:45.877
The world's opening up faster

03:45.921 --> 03:47.227
than we can replenish
our stores.

03:47.270 --> 03:49.620
We're one major accident away
from catastrophe.

03:49.664 --> 03:50.795
- Okay, okay.
Don't worry.

03:50.839 --> 03:52.232
You manage what little
we've got left,

03:52.275 --> 03:53.537
and I will get
the blood flowing.

03:53.581 --> 03:54.582
- I love your enthusiasm,

03:54.625 --> 03:55.844
but blood drives
aren't as easy--

03:55.887 --> 03:57.280
- I got this.

03:57.324 --> 03:58.542
- Oh.

04:00.718 --> 04:01.893
- Sandra Fall from billing?

04:01.937 --> 04:03.504
- Max Goodwin,
the dark overlord.

04:03.547 --> 04:05.549
- Ouch, when did that happen?
- When I got downsized.

04:05.593 --> 04:07.725
- Oh, sorry.
There have been too many cuts.

04:07.769 --> 04:09.118
- Well, how am I supposed
to cover my rent

04:09.161 --> 04:10.337
or pay my bills?

04:10.380 --> 04:12.600
I'm gonna have to fight my cat
for food.

04:12.643 --> 04:13.731
- Wait, no, you won't

04:13.775 --> 04:14.906
because I just had
a great idea.

04:14.950 --> 04:16.734
You can be
my new executive assistant.

04:16.778 --> 04:18.519
You are rehired.
Where are you going?

04:18.562 --> 04:19.737
- To find a nice street corner

04:19.781 --> 04:21.565
where I can beg for change
and recyclables.

04:21.609 --> 04:23.306
- Come on.
It's not that bad of a gig.

04:23.350 --> 04:24.568
- Oh, no?
What happened to Dora?

04:24.612 --> 04:26.570
- Dora quit.
- Oh, what happened to Adele?

04:26.614 --> 04:28.529
- Adele died--
- What?

04:28.572 --> 04:29.660
- Of natural causes.

04:29.704 --> 04:30.748
It had nothing to do
with this job.

04:30.792 --> 04:31.967
Listen, I really need your help

04:32.010 --> 04:33.664
putting together
a hospital blood drive.

04:33.708 --> 04:35.536
It is an emergency situation.

04:35.579 --> 04:37.189
It's got to be fast,
impactful, efficient,

04:37.233 --> 04:40.497
and when I think efficient,
I think of Sandra--ow.

04:40.541 --> 04:41.759
Okay, just for the day?
- I gotta go.

04:41.803 --> 04:43.761
- Please, just for the good
of humanity?

04:43.805 --> 04:47.504
How about for your cat's
nutritional autonomy?

04:47.548 --> 04:48.853
- Fine.
- Really?

04:48.897 --> 04:50.551
- I'll do it for Lilith. Okay?
- Yes, fantastic.

04:50.594 --> 04:51.595
Thank you--
- Okay, no hugging!

04:51.639 --> 04:53.249
No, no, no.
Six feet apart.

04:53.293 --> 04:55.556
And, surprisingly, I've turned
into a compulsive handwasher,

04:55.599 --> 04:57.297
so if you can't find me,
that's where I'll be.

04:57.340 --> 04:59.168
- Right, good.

04:59.211 --> 05:02.258
Great.
My office?

05:02.302 --> 05:03.825
- [sighs]

05:05.261 --> 05:07.916
[keypad beeping]

05:11.354 --> 05:14.270
- My spy craft is
really on point today.

05:14.314 --> 05:15.358
You sleep okay?

05:15.402 --> 05:16.664
- Yeah.

05:19.841 --> 05:21.973
- Oh, wow.

05:22.017 --> 05:25.020
Wow, I haven't seen
one of these in ages.

05:25.063 --> 05:27.414
What's on a Leyla playlist?

05:27.457 --> 05:30.068
- I have to go.

05:30.112 --> 05:32.593
- You sure you don't wanna
leave that here?

05:32.636 --> 05:34.290
Mi casa es su casa,

05:34.334 --> 05:36.336
or a closet in this case.

05:38.381 --> 05:39.687
No one's gonna touch it

05:39.730 --> 05:42.080
or your ancient iPod.

05:51.568 --> 05:53.483
Oh, that's gonna make
a huge difference.

06:04.668 --> 06:06.757
- Okay.
Good talk.

06:10.370 --> 06:13.460
- Operation Blood Flow is a go.

06:13.503 --> 06:16.419
[percussive music]

06:16.463 --> 06:18.247
♪

06:18.290 --> 06:19.814
I should start knocking.

06:19.857 --> 06:21.250
- No, no.

06:21.293 --> 06:22.556
I'll leave you guys to it.

06:22.599 --> 06:27.648
♪

06:27.691 --> 06:29.171
- Thank you, Dr. Shin.

06:36.091 --> 06:37.484
- Yes.

06:37.527 --> 06:39.921
So you have an idea
for this Operation Blood Flow?

06:39.964 --> 06:42.314
- Yeah--no, uh...

06:42.358 --> 06:43.794
It j--

06:43.838 --> 06:45.579
just needs some retooling.

06:47.972 --> 06:49.539
- Okay, do you want
to talk it over?

06:49.583 --> 06:51.236
- Talk about...

06:51.280 --> 06:52.368
no.

06:52.412 --> 06:53.804
Yeah--no.

06:53.848 --> 06:56.285
Minor tweaks, little stuff.

06:56.328 --> 06:58.156
It's--you know.

06:58.200 --> 06:59.375
Yeah, I got it.

06:59.419 --> 07:00.768
I got this.

07:04.511 --> 07:08.428
- [sighs]

07:08.471 --> 07:10.212
- As our new
associate trauma surgeon,

07:10.255 --> 07:12.432
your primary job will be
backing up Cassian.

07:12.475 --> 07:13.911
- Understood.

07:13.955 --> 07:15.565
- You do realize that
that means a lot less surgery

07:15.609 --> 07:16.871
than you're used to, right?

07:16.914 --> 07:18.699
- Not a problem.
Just put me to work.

07:18.742 --> 07:19.961
- Yeah, the ED is not
like the OR.

07:20.004 --> 07:21.266
I can't just--

07:21.310 --> 07:22.572
- Anesthesia's tubing a patient
in bay six,

07:22.616 --> 07:24.095
and we're out of Midazolam.

07:24.139 --> 07:26.489
- Midazolam. Midazolam...

07:28.622 --> 07:30.362
- What are you--whoa!
Hey!

07:30.406 --> 07:31.494
Careful.

07:33.583 --> 07:36.151
- Aha!
- What the hell?

07:36.194 --> 07:38.501
- Pharmacy is always running
out of the drugs that we need,

07:38.545 --> 07:40.721
so we keep a secret stash
in the ceiling.

07:40.764 --> 07:42.505
- Is that legal?
- Don't ask.

07:42.549 --> 07:45.290
Like I was saying, the ED is
not structured like the OR.

07:45.334 --> 07:46.596
It's like jazz.

07:46.640 --> 07:47.771
You gotta go with the flow.

07:47.815 --> 07:49.469
Get in the rhythm.
Improvise.

07:49.512 --> 07:50.644
- Okay.

07:50.687 --> 07:52.863
I like jazz.

07:52.907 --> 07:55.562
- Elisa Barkley,
16-year-old restrained driver

07:55.605 --> 07:57.346
of a car T-boned
by a speeding taxi.

07:57.389 --> 07:58.782
Tachy, multiple hip fractures,

07:58.826 --> 08:00.262
deep laceration
on the upper thigh.

08:00.305 --> 08:01.872
Lost a large volume of blood
at the scene

08:01.916 --> 08:03.526
and became hypotensive
in the field.

08:03.570 --> 08:05.223
- Please, help my daughter.

08:05.267 --> 08:08.009
- Ma'am, we're gonna take care
of both of you.

08:08.052 --> 08:10.925
- Unstable pelvis.
Book an OR.

08:10.968 --> 08:12.709
I'll need at least two units
of trauma blood.

08:12.753 --> 08:14.145
- Two units is all we've got.

08:14.189 --> 08:15.625
- Then I guess
I'm taking it all.

08:15.669 --> 08:18.498
- OR 2.
- All right.

08:18.541 --> 08:20.325
[phone buzzes]
- Yeah.

08:20.369 --> 08:23.894
- We need to divert all
knife fights, GSWs, and MVAs.

08:23.938 --> 08:26.157
And pray no one here has
a massive bleed.

08:26.201 --> 08:27.681
- Why?

08:27.724 --> 08:30.248
- New Amsterdam is officially
out of blood.

08:30.292 --> 08:33.513
[tense music]

08:35.776 --> 08:36.167
.

08:36.211 --> 08:38.300
- We need blood fast.

08:38.343 --> 08:39.954
We gotta target non-sick people
coming into the hospital,

08:39.997 --> 08:41.085
most of whom are parents

08:41.129 --> 08:42.565
who often have their kids
with them,

08:42.609 --> 08:45.220
and what is the one thing
that parents need right now

08:45.263 --> 08:47.352
more than anything?

08:47.396 --> 08:48.484
Time away from their kids.

08:48.528 --> 08:50.791
So the puppies will babysit
the kids,

08:50.834 --> 08:53.533
and we will give the parents
a quiet moment to come in

08:53.576 --> 08:56.057
and give us
their life-saving blood.

08:56.100 --> 08:57.580
- Why not just get
human babysitters?

08:57.624 --> 08:59.669
- Because the puppies were
already on rotation

08:59.713 --> 09:00.670
in the pediatric ward.

09:00.714 --> 09:01.802
- Max.
- Yes?

09:01.845 --> 09:03.020
- Please tell me
you're done retooling

09:03.064 --> 09:04.021
whatever it was
that you were retooling.

09:04.065 --> 09:04.979
- Yeah.
- Hi, Sandra.

09:05.022 --> 09:06.154
- Got a lot done, too.

09:06.197 --> 09:09.549
You were busy doing...
other stuff.

09:09.592 --> 09:11.551
- By other stuff, I assume
you mean finding out

09:11.594 --> 09:13.683
that the one major accident
we were away from catastrophe

09:13.727 --> 09:14.771
just came in?

09:14.815 --> 09:15.990
- That is not what I meant,

09:16.033 --> 09:17.644
but I told you I got this.

09:17.687 --> 09:20.037
So we probably have people
in every seat

09:20.081 --> 09:21.822
lined up around the block.

09:21.865 --> 09:23.171
Take a look for yourself.

09:23.214 --> 09:27.610
[puppies whining and barking]

09:27.654 --> 09:29.090
- Hmm.

09:31.222 --> 09:33.834
You do know that puppy blood
won't work, right?

09:33.877 --> 09:36.837
[percussive music]

09:36.880 --> 09:38.665
♪

09:38.708 --> 09:40.231
- Okay, my veterans.

09:40.275 --> 09:41.668
Everyone here tested negative.

09:41.711 --> 09:42.799
Congrats.

09:42.843 --> 09:44.845
Let's all take a seat
and get started.

09:44.888 --> 09:46.673
All right?

09:46.716 --> 09:49.023
Um...

09:49.066 --> 09:50.981
Chance, hi.

09:51.025 --> 09:52.679
Really glad you made it.

09:52.722 --> 09:54.332
Everybody, I'd like
to introduce a new recruit.

09:54.376 --> 09:55.725
This is PFC Chance Becker.

09:55.769 --> 09:57.031
He is a cavalry scout

09:57.074 --> 09:58.859
from the 101st Airborne, yes?

09:58.902 --> 10:00.469
Yeah.

10:00.512 --> 10:02.732
Chance, in our one-on-one's,
expressed a little reluctance

10:02.776 --> 10:04.038
at joining this group,

10:04.081 --> 10:05.561
but I assured him
that there's no safer place

10:05.605 --> 10:06.954
than here with his sisters
and brothers,

10:06.997 --> 10:09.130
and he's coming up
on a really tough anniversary.

10:09.173 --> 10:11.001
I thought maybe he could use
a little support.

10:11.045 --> 10:12.568
So welcome.

10:12.612 --> 10:14.309
[applause]
Good for you.

10:14.352 --> 10:15.615
- Thanks, guys.

10:17.268 --> 10:18.400
- Here for you, man.

10:18.443 --> 10:19.706
- Yeah, we've all
lost something,

10:19.749 --> 10:21.795
so go ahead.

10:25.581 --> 10:27.322
- We were, um...

10:34.329 --> 10:36.679
Our convoy, it was...

10:36.723 --> 10:39.856
heading towards an OP
in Kandahar Province.

10:39.900 --> 10:43.730
And we took direct contact
from an AQ element.

10:45.079 --> 10:47.298
Four of my squad members,

10:47.342 --> 10:49.083
they were in the lead vehicle

10:49.126 --> 10:51.476
when it got slammed by RPGs.

10:52.652 --> 10:53.783
It was...

10:53.827 --> 10:56.917
[solemn music]

10:56.960 --> 11:00.311
Our driver kinda ran us
off the road, and...

11:00.355 --> 11:02.618
I jumped out.

11:02.662 --> 11:05.360
We were taking small arms fire,
but I just...

11:06.796 --> 11:08.145
But...

11:08.189 --> 11:11.279
I just ran
towards the wreckage.

11:11.322 --> 11:13.281
All I could think was to...

11:13.324 --> 11:15.675
dig out my brothers
and sisters.

11:15.718 --> 11:20.984
♪

11:21.028 --> 11:22.594
Flames, fuel.

11:24.684 --> 11:27.382
I could barely hold it
together.

11:27.425 --> 11:30.385
I called battalion
for a medevac, but...

11:33.344 --> 11:35.912
They were already gone.

11:38.610 --> 11:39.742
- Wow.

11:39.786 --> 11:46.706
♪

11:48.969 --> 11:50.579
- Hey, now. Hey, hey, hey.
- Oh, my God. Rhonda!

11:50.622 --> 11:52.450
What are you doing?
- This guy's a fobbit!

11:52.494 --> 11:53.887
He's a what?
- I was there!

11:53.930 --> 11:56.150
- Then how'd you call it in?
The medevac.

11:56.193 --> 11:58.718
- I used--
I called HQ.

11:58.761 --> 12:00.894
- No way
this guy's seen combat.

12:00.937 --> 12:03.200
- What--okay,
what are you talking about?

12:03.244 --> 12:05.115
- He didn't return
suppressor fire

12:05.159 --> 12:06.508
when they got hit.

12:06.551 --> 12:09.859
And no one calls HQ
for a nine line medevac.

12:11.295 --> 12:12.906
- Okay.

12:12.949 --> 12:14.516
- There are protocols.

12:14.559 --> 12:16.997
We all follow them,
or people die.

12:17.040 --> 12:18.738
He's a fake.

12:18.781 --> 12:21.741
[tense music]

12:21.784 --> 12:23.525
♪

12:23.568 --> 12:24.961
- Nothing has changed.

12:25.005 --> 12:27.485
I--I just woke up blind.

12:27.529 --> 12:29.574
- Okay, let's take a look.

12:33.230 --> 12:34.275
- What about work?

12:34.318 --> 12:35.624
- It's not my job.

12:37.234 --> 12:38.932
- Ms. Castillo.

12:38.975 --> 12:40.281
It's really important

12:40.324 --> 12:41.891
that I have
all the information.

12:44.285 --> 12:46.722
- If they close the factory,

12:46.766 --> 12:50.378
me and my friends will be
out of work again.

12:50.421 --> 12:52.946
We already lost our jobs
during the shutdowns.

12:52.989 --> 12:54.991
We can't lose this, too.

12:55.035 --> 12:57.254
We're still paying off
our rent deferral.

12:57.298 --> 12:59.866
- HIPAA privacy laws prevent us

12:59.909 --> 13:01.389
from disclosing
anything you tell us

13:01.432 --> 13:03.783
without your consent.

13:03.826 --> 13:05.132
Please.

13:05.175 --> 13:06.786
This may help me treat you.

13:08.439 --> 13:10.833
- I work in a plastics factory.

13:10.877 --> 13:11.878
Off the books.

13:11.921 --> 13:13.488
It's the only work
I could find.

13:16.317 --> 13:18.058
- I think
you may have been exposed

13:18.101 --> 13:20.451
to diboron tetrabromide.

13:20.495 --> 13:23.367
It can trigger vasospasm
in the retinal artery,

13:23.411 --> 13:25.152
which is probably what's
causing your blindness.

13:25.195 --> 13:26.893
- Probably?

13:26.936 --> 13:28.372
- Well, it's a theory.

13:28.416 --> 13:29.765
- Can you fix it?

13:29.809 --> 13:31.114
- I think so.

13:31.158 --> 13:34.161
I mean, yes, definitely.

13:34.204 --> 13:35.466
Maybe.

13:41.385 --> 13:43.997
- Am I going to look
like Frankenstein now?

13:44.040 --> 13:45.520
- Oh, not at all.

13:45.563 --> 13:46.826
These are what you call

13:46.869 --> 13:49.089
subcuticular continuous
sutures, all right?

13:49.132 --> 13:50.742
By the time I'm done,

13:50.786 --> 13:53.223
you won't even have a scar.

13:53.267 --> 13:55.095
- Dr. Reynolds.

13:55.138 --> 13:56.836
A word?

13:56.879 --> 13:57.967
- Excuse me.

14:00.970 --> 14:03.625
- How long have you been
stitching for?

14:03.668 --> 14:05.105
- I don't know.
I wasn't keeping track--

14:05.148 --> 14:06.149
- Exactly.

14:06.193 --> 14:07.411
Okay, this is not the place

14:07.455 --> 14:09.152
where you can take your time
making sure

14:09.196 --> 14:10.632
every suture is
textbook perfect.

14:10.675 --> 14:12.982
We are a conveyor belt
that never stops moving.

14:13.026 --> 14:15.463
- So you want me to do
a less good job on my patients?

14:15.506 --> 14:16.943
- No, no, not less good.

14:16.986 --> 14:18.335
Faster.
Jazz.

14:18.379 --> 14:19.510
- Look, you wanna talk jazz?

14:19.554 --> 14:20.685
Miles Davis?

14:20.729 --> 14:21.904
Following my own meter,

14:21.948 --> 14:23.471
especially when it comes
to my patients.

14:23.514 --> 14:25.952
- Okay, Miles.
Well, look.

14:25.995 --> 14:27.475
Here is what backed up

14:27.518 --> 14:28.868
while you were inching your way

14:28.911 --> 14:31.348
through that superficial
four-centimeter scalp lac.

14:31.392 --> 14:33.046
Go ahead,
follow your own meter.

14:33.089 --> 14:35.222
You should be done
by next Wednesday.

14:35.265 --> 14:39.008
[percussive jazz music]

14:39.052 --> 14:40.401
- Thank you.

14:40.444 --> 14:41.924
- Hey, guys.
What are you doing?

14:41.968 --> 14:42.882
- Scheduled maintenance.

14:42.925 --> 14:44.231
- There was a backpack in here.

14:44.274 --> 14:46.407
A puke-orange backpack.

14:46.450 --> 14:47.495
Where is it?

14:47.538 --> 14:48.670
- Don't know.

14:48.713 --> 14:50.106
- Well, it was here
this morning.

14:50.150 --> 14:51.107
- I'm sorry.

14:55.416 --> 14:57.897
- No, no, no, no, no...

15:01.901 --> 15:03.467
- Thank you for letting me
do this.

15:03.511 --> 15:04.947
- Not at all.

15:04.991 --> 15:08.385
Family members often donate
for a loved one's surgery.

15:08.429 --> 15:10.300
Actually, you're doing us
a favor.

15:10.344 --> 15:12.346
Blood's in short supply
right now.

15:12.389 --> 15:14.565
- Take as much as you need.

15:14.609 --> 15:16.176
Take it all.

15:16.219 --> 15:17.829
I'd do anything for my baby.

15:19.527 --> 15:21.050
I'm sorry.

15:21.094 --> 15:23.531
Elisa always says
I'm being melodramatic.

15:23.574 --> 15:26.186
- [laughs]
And teenagers never are.

15:26.229 --> 15:28.101
- I just need her to be okay.

15:28.144 --> 15:31.365
[tense music]

15:31.408 --> 15:32.627
- What's wrong?

15:35.064 --> 15:36.500
- Was, um...

15:36.544 --> 15:38.546
was Elisa adopted?

15:38.589 --> 15:42.115
- I was in labor with her
for 31 hours.

15:42.158 --> 15:44.160
- Did you use an egg donor?

15:44.204 --> 15:47.207
- No, her father and I did it
the old-fashioned way.

15:47.250 --> 15:48.599
What's going on?

15:48.643 --> 15:52.516
♪

15:52.560 --> 15:55.258
[machines beeping]

15:55.302 --> 15:57.652
- Were you able to stretch
the two units of blood?

15:57.695 --> 15:59.306
- Just about.

15:59.349 --> 16:01.917
Why? Was her mom not a match?

16:01.961 --> 16:03.049
- No.

16:03.092 --> 16:05.007
But it's more than that.

16:05.051 --> 16:06.269
- What do you mean?

16:06.313 --> 16:07.923
- With their blood types,

16:07.967 --> 16:10.056
there's no way
she's Elisa's biological mum.

16:16.018 --> 16:16.192
.

16:16.236 --> 16:18.934
- This is what we should've
been doing the whole time.

16:18.978 --> 16:20.283
I mean, puppies are
a great incentive for kids,

16:20.327 --> 16:21.937
but this is not
the right incentive for adults.

16:21.981 --> 16:23.025
What they need is--
- Money?

16:23.069 --> 16:25.027
- No, this is about
more than money.

16:25.071 --> 16:27.334
It's about tapping in to what
people have really been missing

16:27.377 --> 16:28.596
during this pandemic, you know?

16:28.639 --> 16:30.293
Something that feeds
every New Yorker's soul.

16:30.337 --> 16:31.642
- Complaining
about subway delays?

16:31.686 --> 16:33.253
- Ye--no. Restaurants.

16:33.296 --> 16:35.733
Eating out.
Experiencing something new.

16:35.777 --> 16:38.562
Something you can only get
right here in New York.

16:38.606 --> 16:41.739
So we are giving everyone
who donates blood a free meal.

16:41.783 --> 16:43.350
And not just any meal.

16:43.393 --> 16:45.221
A multi-course tasting menu

16:45.265 --> 16:47.180
by a Michelin star chef.

16:47.223 --> 16:48.659
- First, we're gonna
bleed them.

16:48.703 --> 16:50.400
Then we're gonna feed them.
- That's actually good.

16:50.444 --> 16:52.272
So I called Elena Roca.
- Oh, love her.

16:52.315 --> 16:54.448
- Yeah, and she agreed
to donate her staff

16:54.491 --> 16:55.623
and her food.

16:55.666 --> 16:56.667
Who could resist?

16:58.930 --> 17:00.062
- Wow.

17:00.106 --> 17:02.673
They seem to be resisting
just fine.

17:02.717 --> 17:04.110
[dog barking]

17:04.153 --> 17:07.113
[percussive music]

17:07.156 --> 17:11.508
♪

17:12.988 --> 17:14.468
- All I did was tell my story.

17:14.511 --> 17:16.339
- Okay, that's great.
Let's talk about that.

17:16.383 --> 17:17.297
Sit down.

17:18.907 --> 17:20.430
I have a feeling

17:20.474 --> 17:23.042
that you have been telling
that story for quite some time,

17:23.085 --> 17:24.478
and I think that you would
really like that

17:24.521 --> 17:25.348
to be your story.

17:25.392 --> 17:27.524
- I'm not lying.
- Chance.

17:28.917 --> 17:30.266
I have a buddy at the VA
who told me

17:30.310 --> 17:32.007
that you are not in the system.

17:33.269 --> 17:34.879
You're not in
the Choice Program.

17:34.923 --> 17:36.142
Nothing.

17:39.101 --> 17:41.103
You are trying to fill a void
in you.

17:41.147 --> 17:43.279
You are not alone in that.

17:43.323 --> 17:45.151
But the way you're trying
to fill it...

17:47.892 --> 17:50.547
It's called stolen valor.

17:50.591 --> 17:52.027
It's not real.

17:55.074 --> 17:58.512
You were never in Afghanistan,
were you?

17:58.555 --> 18:00.470
There was no ambush.
There were no burned bodies.

18:00.514 --> 18:03.995
- Do you know the smell
of burning flesh?

18:04.039 --> 18:06.607
It's sickening.

18:06.650 --> 18:07.695
Never leaves you.

18:07.738 --> 18:10.089
You smell it everywhere.

18:10.132 --> 18:13.831
A match, a candle,
a grill in the park.

18:13.875 --> 18:15.181
All of it brings it back.

18:15.224 --> 18:18.097
I can't go anywhere
without them following me.

18:19.489 --> 18:22.753
Don't tell me
the flames weren't real.

18:22.797 --> 18:25.756
[dramatic music]

18:25.800 --> 18:31.110
♪

18:31.153 --> 18:34.330
[beeping]

18:34.374 --> 18:36.637
- Push 2 milligrams
Ativan IV.

18:36.680 --> 18:38.813
- Pushing 2 milligrams
Ativan IV.

18:38.856 --> 18:42.469
- Diboron tetrabromide exposure
doesn't cause seizures.

18:44.384 --> 18:46.734
I don't know what's wrong
with her.

18:53.219 --> 18:55.699
- There's a small anomaly here.

18:57.310 --> 18:58.876
- I don't see anything.

18:58.920 --> 19:01.227
- Right here.

19:04.839 --> 19:07.189
- Guess that could explain
Rose's symptoms.

19:07.233 --> 19:08.625
It's really small.

19:08.669 --> 19:10.584
- Well, look, you asked
for my opinion?

19:10.627 --> 19:13.717
This is why the Verapamil
didn't work.

19:13.761 --> 19:16.067
- So I should start her
on Phenytoin?

19:16.111 --> 19:18.287
- If you want her
to get better.

19:20.855 --> 19:22.204
- I don't know.

19:22.248 --> 19:23.597
- Dr. Kao?

19:23.640 --> 19:24.989
- Yes?

19:25.033 --> 19:26.774
- It's what
Dr. Kapoor would do.

19:30.734 --> 19:34.085
- Anita, the test results
were incompatible

19:34.129 --> 19:35.913
with parental relation.

19:35.957 --> 19:37.263
- What does that even mean?

19:40.962 --> 19:42.572
Are you--

19:45.532 --> 19:48.448
Are...are you saying Elisa is
not my daughter?

19:50.058 --> 19:51.712
- I'm hoping it's a mistake
our end.

19:51.755 --> 19:53.757
A simple DNA test will clear--
- Clear what?

19:53.801 --> 19:56.456
Do you think I hallucinated
giving birth to her?

19:56.499 --> 19:58.414
Do you think I stole her?

19:58.458 --> 19:59.502
- No one is saying that.

19:59.546 --> 20:01.200
- Then what are you saying?

20:01.243 --> 20:03.637
How could my child not be
my child?

20:05.116 --> 20:06.683
- If she was switched at birth.

20:10.470 --> 20:12.254
I honestly wish I didn't have
to bring this up,

20:12.298 --> 20:13.864
but I am duty-bound
not just to you,

20:13.908 --> 20:15.779
but if there is another family
out there--

20:15.823 --> 20:16.911
- Elisa's my child.

20:16.954 --> 20:17.999
- Emotionally, of course.

20:18.042 --> 20:20.131
- If the biological...

20:20.175 --> 20:22.221
truth or whatever's different,

20:22.264 --> 20:24.571
I don't want to know.

20:24.614 --> 20:25.789
- I do.

20:27.835 --> 20:29.140
- Elisa?

20:29.184 --> 20:33.101
[solemn music]

20:33.144 --> 20:34.798
- I want the test.

20:34.842 --> 20:41.370
♪

20:41.414 --> 20:43.024
- Whatcha looking for?

20:43.067 --> 20:44.460
- An orange backpack.

20:44.504 --> 20:46.984
Very heavy,
incredibly important.

20:47.028 --> 20:48.769
- Oh, no.
What was in it?

20:48.812 --> 20:50.336
- I have no idea.

20:50.379 --> 20:52.033
- Kevin McGlynn, 65.

20:52.076 --> 20:53.295
Complaining of nausea

20:53.339 --> 20:55.166
and sudden abdominal
and lower back pain.

20:55.210 --> 20:56.820
- Tachy?
- 140 BPM.

20:56.864 --> 20:58.779
Thinking a leaking abdominal
aortic aneurism.

20:58.822 --> 21:00.171
- Well, then why'd you
bring him here?

21:00.215 --> 21:01.738
We went on diversion
four hours ago.

21:01.782 --> 21:03.087
- You're not the only ones
diverting.

21:03.131 --> 21:04.306
Blood shortage is citywide.

21:04.350 --> 21:05.655
- Yeah, that's
a pulsatile mass.

21:05.699 --> 21:08.005
Grab Reynolds.
- Oh, he took lunch.

21:08.049 --> 21:09.485
- He took lunch?

21:09.529 --> 21:11.226
- You probably want me to go--
- Find him now.

21:11.270 --> 21:13.097
With me, Trauma One.

21:13.141 --> 21:16.057
[suspenseful music]

21:16.100 --> 21:18.364
♪

21:18.407 --> 21:19.669
Prepare to intubate.

21:19.713 --> 21:21.497
Insert a Foley
and two large bore IVs.

21:21.541 --> 21:22.455
- On it.

21:22.498 --> 21:23.630
- Please tell me
you found blood.

21:23.673 --> 21:24.761
- No.

21:24.805 --> 21:25.806
We've got to be ready
for open repair.

21:25.849 --> 21:26.894
His AAA could blow
at any minute.

21:26.937 --> 21:28.112
- We're gonna do this
without blood?

21:28.156 --> 21:31.333
- You got a better idea?

21:31.377 --> 21:32.726
Nice lunch?
- Yeah.

21:32.769 --> 21:34.989
I usually take lunch at 1:00.
- Yeah, not anymore.

21:35.032 --> 21:37.687
Here, we eat on the go
when you can if you can.

21:41.387 --> 21:42.605
- I don't know, I don't know,
I don't know.

21:42.649 --> 21:44.041
I don't know what to believe.

21:44.085 --> 21:45.695
I know that I've lost the trust
of my vet's group.

21:45.739 --> 21:49.351
I know that,
but now I feel like, um...

21:49.395 --> 21:51.048
I feel like
I've missed something.

21:51.092 --> 21:52.223
You know?

21:52.267 --> 21:53.486
I do know
that Chance is suffering.

21:53.529 --> 21:54.878
- You think he's telling
the truth?

21:54.922 --> 21:57.359
- I think that he's telling
a truth, yeah.

21:57.403 --> 21:59.056
- Did you Google him?
- Gladys.

21:59.100 --> 22:00.362
I refuse to believe

22:00.406 --> 22:01.842
that that is what
our profession has come to.

22:01.885 --> 22:03.670
Okay?
And yeah, I did, obviously.

22:03.713 --> 22:05.802
I couldn't find anything.
[phone rings]

22:07.848 --> 22:09.676
Chance?

22:09.719 --> 22:11.242
No, no, no, no.
No, don't say that.

22:11.286 --> 22:12.635
Listen to me.

22:12.679 --> 22:14.681
No, listen, listen.
Just tell me where you are.

22:14.724 --> 22:16.422
Chance, tell me where you are.

22:19.076 --> 22:20.861
Chance.
- You did this!

22:20.904 --> 22:23.603
- Wait, wait, wait, wait.
Wait, no, stop, stop!

22:25.953 --> 22:27.389
Chance, stop, stop, stop!
- Don't! Don't!

22:27.433 --> 22:28.390
- Oh, my God, stop!

22:28.434 --> 22:29.957
- Don't!
- Chance.

22:30.000 --> 22:31.437
Okay.

22:34.831 --> 22:35.049
.

22:35.092 --> 22:37.399
- Okay, okay, okay!
- Don't! Stay back!

22:37.443 --> 22:39.227
[coughs]

22:39.270 --> 22:40.881
You made me go
to that stupid group.

22:40.924 --> 22:42.056
- I did.
I know, I know.

22:42.099 --> 22:43.362
I'm sorry.
I shouldn't have done that.

22:43.405 --> 22:44.754
Chance, I shouldn't have
done that, but I'm here.

22:44.798 --> 22:45.799
Please, talk to me.

22:45.842 --> 22:47.409
- Why?
You don't believe me!

22:47.453 --> 22:49.106
- Yes, I do!
I believe--I believe--

22:49.150 --> 22:50.238
I believe your burns are real.

22:50.281 --> 22:52.545
I believe your pain
is very real.

22:52.588 --> 22:54.285
Chance, look at me!

22:54.329 --> 22:56.157
I believe you.

22:56.200 --> 22:57.941
There was a fire, wasn't there?

22:58.986 --> 23:00.814
There was a fire.

23:00.857 --> 23:01.902
People lie.
People do that.

23:01.945 --> 23:03.164
People lie to impress.

23:03.207 --> 23:05.514
People lie to hide their shame.

23:05.558 --> 23:06.994
I lie to hide my pain.

23:07.037 --> 23:08.430
I do it every day.

23:09.736 --> 23:12.042
Where was the fire?
Tell me where the fire was.

23:12.086 --> 23:13.783
Tell me something.

23:13.827 --> 23:16.395
Tell me one--one true thing.

23:16.438 --> 23:19.615
[tense music]

23:19.659 --> 23:21.791
- It was upstate.

23:21.835 --> 23:23.445
- Okay, upstate.

23:23.489 --> 23:25.926
There, we started.

23:25.969 --> 23:27.797
That's where
your family's from, right?

23:29.320 --> 23:31.540
That's why you contacted me,
isn't it?

23:31.584 --> 23:33.107
Part of you wanted
to unburden yourself.

23:33.150 --> 23:34.761
You want to tell me the truth.

23:34.804 --> 23:36.197
I'm here.
Tell me.

23:36.240 --> 23:37.328
I'm here.

23:39.766 --> 23:41.594
- I was--

23:41.637 --> 23:43.552
I was drunk.

23:44.858 --> 23:46.816
[sobbing]

23:46.860 --> 23:49.863
The farm, my family's farm.

23:49.906 --> 23:51.778
- What happened?

23:51.821 --> 23:54.258
- It was a--a cigarette.

23:54.302 --> 23:56.435
It--

23:56.478 --> 23:57.958
it lit up the barn

23:58.001 --> 23:59.525
and then the house,

23:59.568 --> 24:03.442
and then by the time
I heard them screaming...

24:03.485 --> 24:05.400
I tried to stop it.

24:07.010 --> 24:09.491
My brother,

24:09.535 --> 24:10.623
my big sister,

24:10.666 --> 24:12.276
my parents, gone.

24:13.974 --> 24:16.498
- An accident, an accident,
an accident!

24:16.542 --> 24:17.847
An accident, Chance.

24:17.891 --> 24:19.806
- Does it matter?
- Yes, it matters.

24:19.849 --> 24:22.156
All of it matters
because it's real.

24:22.199 --> 24:24.419
It is your truth.
Do you understand?

24:26.203 --> 24:29.032
All the rest of it,
you need to let go.

24:30.599 --> 24:32.035
You need to just let it go.

24:32.079 --> 24:35.038
[solemn music]

24:35.082 --> 24:42.219
♪

24:44.831 --> 24:47.529
- Rose, it's Dr. Kao.

24:47.573 --> 24:50.663
I've got some new medication
for you.

24:50.706 --> 24:53.492
This one will work.

24:53.535 --> 24:54.928
- [inhales sharply]

24:54.971 --> 24:56.320
- Sorry, did I scare you?

24:56.364 --> 24:58.366
- No.

24:58.409 --> 25:01.543
- Then why did you pull away?

25:01.587 --> 25:03.414
- I don't know.

25:05.634 --> 25:08.202
- Did something happen?

25:08.245 --> 25:10.509
Did someone hurt you?

25:10.552 --> 25:14.295
- [crying]

25:16.515 --> 25:17.994
- When?

25:19.909 --> 25:21.868
- A month ago.

25:21.911 --> 25:29.092
♪

25:33.967 --> 25:37.100
I was walking home one night.

25:37.144 --> 25:39.059
These two white guys,

25:39.102 --> 25:41.757
they jumped me.

25:41.801 --> 25:43.585
Beat me to the ground.

25:43.629 --> 25:47.284
Blamed me for bringing
the virus to America.

25:49.286 --> 25:50.853
I'm Filipina,
but all they see is--

25:50.897 --> 25:52.246
- I know.

25:55.075 --> 25:56.337
Why didn't you tell me?

25:56.380 --> 25:59.079
- It was so long ago, and...

25:59.122 --> 26:00.733
I protected my head.

26:00.776 --> 26:03.083
What would that have to do
with blindness?

26:06.042 --> 26:08.871
- Did they hit
your abdominal area?

26:08.915 --> 26:11.004
- Yes.

26:11.047 --> 26:12.571
Over and over.

26:14.094 --> 26:15.748
- Rose.

26:15.791 --> 26:19.316
I think your liver was damaged
in the attack.

26:19.360 --> 26:21.449
But because it happened
weeks ago,

26:21.492 --> 26:24.583
your blood tests looked normal.

26:24.626 --> 26:29.022
But most of your liver is
now not functioning.

26:34.070 --> 26:35.855
It's okay.

26:35.898 --> 26:38.161
We can treat it.

26:38.205 --> 26:40.337
Without a doubt.

26:44.472 --> 26:46.779
- We're not doing the test.

26:46.822 --> 26:48.955
- Why do you get to make
that decision for me?

26:48.998 --> 26:52.045
- Because I'm your mother.

26:52.088 --> 26:53.655
- Maybe.

26:53.699 --> 26:55.004
- What?

26:55.048 --> 26:56.440
- Maybe!

26:56.484 --> 26:58.486
- Okay, let's all just
take a breath.

26:58.529 --> 27:00.444
- You are not who I want
to hear from right now.

27:00.488 --> 27:01.663
- Why can't you understand?

27:01.707 --> 27:03.665
I wanna know where I belong.

27:03.709 --> 27:05.493
- You belong with me.

27:09.192 --> 27:10.759
- Look at our hands.

27:13.457 --> 27:14.720
Our skin.

27:16.983 --> 27:18.375
You don't get it.

27:20.334 --> 27:22.728
I've always felt different.

27:22.771 --> 27:26.166
I've always looked different.

27:26.209 --> 27:28.385
From the entire family.

27:30.344 --> 27:32.128
I've always felt
like an outsider.

27:32.172 --> 27:33.826
- Baby, that's the world
saying that,

27:33.869 --> 27:35.654
not me, not your family.

27:38.265 --> 27:40.789
I've never treated you
different.

27:40.833 --> 27:42.486
How could you even think
something so hurt--

27:42.530 --> 27:44.750
- Here comes the melodrama.

27:44.793 --> 27:46.882
There is no way you're my--

27:46.926 --> 27:48.623
- We don't need a DNA test.

27:50.451 --> 27:52.105
But I do need a biopsy.

27:52.148 --> 27:53.193
- Why?

27:53.236 --> 27:55.456
- Because you could both
be right.

27:58.024 --> 27:59.373
- Where's all this blood
coming from?

27:59.416 --> 28:01.549
- His AAA just ruptured.

28:01.592 --> 28:03.682
Okay, I'm gonna stabilize
the arterial stump

28:03.725 --> 28:06.510
while you cross-clamp
the aorta.

28:06.554 --> 28:10.079
Okay, I have the arterial edge
with my forceps.

28:10.123 --> 28:11.385
- I--I can't see anything.

28:11.428 --> 28:12.865
- Just follow my forceps down.

28:12.908 --> 28:15.041
Cross-clamp just above the tip.

28:15.084 --> 28:16.259
- There are no landmarks.

28:16.303 --> 28:17.870
- Go by feel.

28:17.913 --> 28:19.872
[tense music]

28:19.915 --> 28:21.743
[indistinct chatter]

28:21.787 --> 28:25.965
♪

28:26.008 --> 28:27.053
- Okay, I think I got it.

28:27.096 --> 28:28.532
- Suction.

28:28.576 --> 28:30.534
- ACC time is 100 minutes.

28:30.578 --> 28:32.623
- Bleeding has stopped.
You got it.

28:34.974 --> 28:37.585
- But now his liver, kidneys,
and intestines are toast.

28:37.628 --> 28:38.978
- Not yet.

28:39.021 --> 28:40.501
We got three minutes to find
a replacement aorta.

28:40.544 --> 28:42.024
- You can prepare
a Dacron graft

28:42.068 --> 28:43.112
in three minutes?

28:43.156 --> 28:44.897
- 92.

28:44.940 --> 28:46.420
- Ah.

28:46.463 --> 28:48.291
Give me some of that
suction tubing?

28:49.815 --> 28:51.773
Scissors.

28:51.817 --> 28:54.515
- Sponge count?

28:54.558 --> 28:56.169
- Suture.

28:57.866 --> 28:59.128
- The hell you doing?

28:59.172 --> 29:01.783
- Say hello to Mr. McGlynn's...

29:01.827 --> 29:03.437
replacement aorta.

29:03.480 --> 29:05.526
- Pared-back space looks clean.

29:05.569 --> 29:08.529
- Until we get him up to the OR
for a proper graft.

29:08.572 --> 29:10.313
- Are you sure about this?

29:12.228 --> 29:13.621
- Jazz, right?

29:17.756 --> 29:19.018
- The ED called.

29:19.061 --> 29:21.237
- I know, diversion is
diverting back to us.

29:21.281 --> 29:22.804
We have got to make this work.

29:22.848 --> 29:25.459
- Max, no one wants fine dining
in the vicinity of nurses

29:25.502 --> 29:27.591
with urine samples,
sick or dying people,

29:27.635 --> 29:28.897
and sirens blaring
in the background.

29:28.941 --> 29:30.377
- I know, but I think
I've got something

29:30.420 --> 29:32.118
that's gonna drown out
those sirens,

29:32.161 --> 29:33.554
that's gonna lift
people's spirits,

29:33.597 --> 29:35.295
and for the love of God,
it's gonna inspire them

29:35.338 --> 29:36.383
to donate blood.

29:36.426 --> 29:38.254
- Alcohol?
- Nope.

29:38.298 --> 29:39.690
Broadway.

29:41.257 --> 29:42.432
Jazz hands.

29:42.476 --> 29:45.000
Too much. Desperation. Sorry.

29:45.044 --> 29:47.611
The performers are
former patients,

29:47.655 --> 29:48.917
and with all
the theaters closed,

29:48.961 --> 29:50.440
they jumped at the opportunity
to perform

29:50.484 --> 29:52.312
for a real-life audience.

29:52.355 --> 29:53.966
- ♪ Down by the riverside

29:54.009 --> 29:55.010
- ♪ Oh, down

29:55.054 --> 29:56.446
- ♪ Down by the riverside

29:56.490 --> 29:57.665
- ♪ Oh, down

29:57.708 --> 29:59.275
- ♪ Down by the riverside

29:59.319 --> 30:01.060
- Oh, come on!

30:01.103 --> 30:02.452
Really?

30:02.496 --> 30:03.976
- ♪ Down by the riverside

30:04.019 --> 30:05.499
- Yeah, no, no, we're good
on the singing.

30:05.542 --> 30:06.892
Stop with the singing, please.

30:06.935 --> 30:08.197
Thank you.

30:11.592 --> 30:13.333
Excuse me, can I ask you
a question?

30:13.376 --> 30:14.638
- Me?
- Yeah.

30:14.682 --> 30:16.640
All these people here are
donating their time,

30:16.684 --> 30:18.468
their talents, their food,
their dogs

30:18.512 --> 30:21.471
to get people like you
to donate their blood,

30:21.515 --> 30:22.864
which is desperately needed.

30:22.908 --> 30:24.648
I see you stopped in,
but not quite biting.

30:24.692 --> 30:28.261
So I was just wondering,
what's it gonna take?

30:28.304 --> 30:30.567
- Do you have any idea

30:30.611 --> 30:32.613
what people are going through
right now?

30:33.962 --> 30:36.443
I'm homeschooling three kids

30:36.486 --> 30:38.662
while taking care
of my ailing father.

30:38.706 --> 30:39.925
I...

30:39.968 --> 30:42.101
I've donated to every cause
under the sun.

30:42.144 --> 30:43.798
I've marched
for social justice.

30:43.842 --> 30:46.105
I've made meals
for the unhoused.

30:46.148 --> 30:48.629
We're done.
Everyone is tapped.

30:49.586 --> 30:50.718
- I know, but--but--

30:50.761 --> 30:52.894
- People have given everything

30:52.938 --> 30:56.245
this past year,
except their blood.

30:56.289 --> 30:58.508
And I, for one, would like
to keep that.

31:01.816 --> 31:04.210
- So that's it?
People are just done giving?

31:04.253 --> 31:07.213
[solemn music]

31:07.256 --> 31:09.432
♪

31:09.476 --> 31:10.912
All right, shut it down.
All of it.

31:10.956 --> 31:12.914
You guys can go.
Get the food out of here.

31:12.958 --> 31:14.263
It's over.

31:24.012 --> 31:24.230
.

31:24.273 --> 31:25.840
- So...?

31:25.884 --> 31:29.888
- Anita, your biopsy revealed
something unusual.

31:29.931 --> 31:33.369
The technical term for it is,
you're a chimera.

31:33.413 --> 31:36.895
You have two different DNAs
in your body.

31:36.938 --> 31:38.592
- How is that possible?

31:38.635 --> 31:39.854
- It's a rare condition

31:39.898 --> 31:41.769
that can happen in utero
in twin pregnancies.

31:41.812 --> 31:43.597
- But I'm not a twin.

31:43.640 --> 31:46.034
- You were.

31:46.078 --> 31:47.514
When you were just an embryo,

31:47.557 --> 31:49.864
you had a fraternal twin
who didn't come to term.

31:49.908 --> 31:50.996
A sister.

31:51.039 --> 31:52.823
In the womb, you absorbed her,

31:52.867 --> 31:54.738
including her ovaries,

31:54.782 --> 31:57.002
and that's the second DNA.

31:57.045 --> 31:58.612
Which is why
the blood test said

31:58.655 --> 31:59.918
you weren't Elisa's mother.

31:59.961 --> 32:02.181
Elisa was born from your body

32:02.224 --> 32:04.792
but from your sister's egg.

32:07.012 --> 32:09.057
- So I'm...

32:09.101 --> 32:12.278
I'm not her daughter?

32:12.321 --> 32:15.063
- Elisa, you may
look different,

32:15.107 --> 32:16.586
but what this proves

32:16.630 --> 32:19.589
is you're actually more
than your mother's daughter.

32:19.633 --> 32:21.113
Not less.

32:23.985 --> 32:26.379
- I'm sorry you felt different.

32:26.422 --> 32:28.990
I should've made you
feel special.

32:30.818 --> 32:32.602
- I guess we both kind of are.

32:32.646 --> 32:35.605
[solemn music]

32:35.649 --> 32:40.132
♪

32:40.175 --> 32:44.049
- Well, I've seen a lot
of AAA open repairs in my time,

32:44.092 --> 32:48.836
but none that used
suction tubing as an aorta.

32:48.879 --> 32:51.926
- I accept
your well-concealed apology.

32:51.970 --> 32:53.319
- Okay.

32:53.362 --> 32:54.929
You've got your way
of doing things,

32:54.973 --> 32:56.322
I've got mine.

32:56.365 --> 32:58.628
Didn't work out
for us personally.

32:58.672 --> 33:02.328
But professionally,
maybe we've got a future.

33:06.419 --> 33:08.290
- Jazz.

33:08.334 --> 33:10.336
- Jazz.

33:12.077 --> 33:13.426
- You looking for this?

33:13.469 --> 33:14.862
- Oh, my God, yes!

33:14.905 --> 33:16.298
Where did you find it?

33:16.342 --> 33:17.604
- I saw the painters
setting up,

33:17.647 --> 33:18.997
and I knew you'd freak.

33:19.040 --> 33:21.869
So I grabbed it and stashed it
in the break room.

33:21.912 --> 33:24.045
- Thank you, thank you,
thank you.

33:24.089 --> 33:25.655
- Yeah, so...

33:25.699 --> 33:27.309
just so I got this straight,

33:27.353 --> 33:30.443
you're letting
a random homeless woman

33:30.486 --> 33:32.140
live in a hospital closet

33:32.184 --> 33:34.012
completely unsupervised.

33:34.055 --> 33:35.622
- Well, when you say it
like that,

33:35.665 --> 33:37.841
it does kind of sound crazy.

33:37.885 --> 33:39.582
- Yeah, that's because it is.

33:39.626 --> 33:41.454
I mean, what do you even know
about this woman?

33:41.497 --> 33:43.151
Or what's in this bag?

33:43.195 --> 33:44.805
- I try to mind
my own business.

33:44.848 --> 33:46.502
- Since when?

33:46.546 --> 33:49.940
Look, you are risking a lot
for a random stranger.

33:49.984 --> 33:51.377
If it were me,

33:51.420 --> 33:54.336
I'd wanna know
who I'm protecting.

33:54.380 --> 34:01.300
♪

34:06.435 --> 34:07.871
- They, uh...

34:07.915 --> 34:10.222
they painted the closet today.

34:10.265 --> 34:12.354
- You went through my stuff,
didn't you?

34:12.398 --> 34:13.834
- Should I have?

34:13.877 --> 34:15.401
Are you hiding something?

34:22.886 --> 34:24.410
Wait, d--

34:30.155 --> 34:31.939
It's nothing.

34:31.982 --> 34:35.073
Why be so protective over it?

34:35.116 --> 34:37.988
- It's nothing to you,
but it's all I have.

34:40.948 --> 34:43.168
- I'm sorry.

34:43.211 --> 34:46.084
It'd just be nice to...

34:46.127 --> 34:48.956
know a little about you,
that's all.

34:48.999 --> 34:51.915
[Cat Stevens' "Into White"]

34:51.959 --> 34:54.918
[soft music]

34:54.962 --> 35:02.100
♪

35:03.840 --> 35:06.582
- I love Punjabi rap.

35:06.626 --> 35:08.106
And...

35:08.149 --> 35:11.065
Hawaiian pizza.

35:11.109 --> 35:12.762
The kind with the pineapple.

35:12.806 --> 35:16.201
But it's so tacky that I would
never tell anyone that.

35:16.244 --> 35:19.378
- It's totally tacky.

35:19.421 --> 35:21.771
- ♪ Windows of light

35:21.815 --> 35:23.469
- Let's go get some.

35:23.512 --> 35:27.037
♪

35:27.081 --> 35:28.300
- ♪ And everything emptying

35:28.343 --> 35:30.824
- Okay.

35:30.867 --> 35:34.088
- ♪ Into white

35:34.132 --> 35:35.785
- This is all you.

35:35.829 --> 35:40.486
♪

35:40.529 --> 35:44.533
It's gonna feel so good
to stop lying to yourself.

35:44.577 --> 35:47.145
You'll see.

35:47.188 --> 35:49.016
Make yourself comfortable,
okay?

35:49.059 --> 35:50.974
- ♪ A simple garden

35:51.018 --> 35:54.064
♪ With acres of sky

35:54.108 --> 35:57.111
♪ A brown-haired dog-mouse

35:57.155 --> 36:00.897
♪ If one dropped by

36:00.941 --> 36:03.987
♪ Yellow Delanie

36:04.031 --> 36:06.947
♪ Would sleep well at night

36:06.990 --> 36:11.560
♪

36:11.604 --> 36:15.390
♪ With everything emptying

36:15.434 --> 36:21.744
♪ Into white

36:23.703 --> 36:25.357
- Dr. Goodwin.

36:25.400 --> 36:26.619
- Thought maybe I should check
on you.

36:26.662 --> 36:28.403
Look over your case load
for today.

36:28.447 --> 36:29.622
- Thanks.

36:29.665 --> 36:31.711
- But I was wrong.

36:31.754 --> 36:33.016
I don't need to check on you
at all.

36:33.060 --> 36:34.757
Rose Castillo?

36:34.801 --> 36:36.542
I don't know any doctor
in this hospital

36:36.585 --> 36:37.978
who could've made
that diagnosis.

36:38.021 --> 36:39.240
I know I couldn't

36:40.633 --> 36:43.070
How did you even think to ask
about her attack?

36:44.158 --> 36:46.682
- Something Dr. Kapoor
taught me.

36:46.726 --> 36:48.815
To watch and listen.

36:48.858 --> 36:52.688
When I touched Rose
to put in her IV, she flinched.

36:54.473 --> 36:57.171
I used to do that, too.

36:57.215 --> 37:00.740
Flinch at little movements
and sounds.

37:00.783 --> 37:02.698
Sometimes, I still do.

37:06.006 --> 37:09.270
When COVID was at its worst,

37:09.314 --> 37:13.535
a man stopped me in the street.

37:13.579 --> 37:15.755
He grabbed my arm

37:15.798 --> 37:18.584
and spat in my face.

37:20.281 --> 37:22.892
Then shoved me aside
like I was nothing.

37:22.936 --> 37:29.247
♪

37:29.290 --> 37:31.510
- Did you talk to anyone?

37:31.553 --> 37:33.338
- No.

37:33.381 --> 37:35.514
It was happening
to so many of us,

37:35.557 --> 37:38.908
and back then,
I just wanted to do my job

37:38.952 --> 37:40.823
and help people.

37:44.087 --> 37:46.089
- Dr. Kao,
I shouldn't have made you

37:46.133 --> 37:47.482
interim, interim chair
of neurology.

37:47.526 --> 37:50.268
That was foolish of me.

37:50.311 --> 37:51.443
I should've made you
interim chair

37:51.486 --> 37:53.793
and not taken no for an answer.

37:53.836 --> 37:55.403
And I know that Dr. Kapoor
would agree

37:55.447 --> 37:57.144
this department is yours

37:57.187 --> 37:58.406
till he comes back.

37:58.450 --> 38:00.321
- ♪ With everything emptying

38:00.365 --> 38:04.194
♪ Into white

38:04.238 --> 38:07.328
♪

38:07.372 --> 38:10.462
[phone buzzing]

38:13.552 --> 38:14.640
Yeah.

38:14.683 --> 38:16.381
- Max, we need you
at the drive.

38:16.424 --> 38:19.601
[soft music]

38:19.645 --> 38:22.561
♪

38:22.604 --> 38:24.345
- Have you given blood
in the last...

38:24.389 --> 38:26.216
- Have you had anything
to eat today?

38:26.260 --> 38:28.828
[indistinct chatter]

38:28.871 --> 38:31.265
- Are you feeling all right?
- Yeah.

38:31.309 --> 38:36.096
♪

38:36.139 --> 38:39.273
[dogs barking]

38:40.927 --> 38:41.884
- [chuckles]

38:41.928 --> 38:45.801
Um...hi.
- Mm-hmm?

38:45.845 --> 38:47.629
- What happened?

38:47.673 --> 38:49.414
- For reasons that escape me,

38:49.457 --> 38:50.980
people are inspired by you.

38:51.024 --> 38:52.112
- Me?
- Yep.

38:52.155 --> 38:53.374
You've asked
the puppy wranglers

38:53.418 --> 38:54.984
and the chefs
and the jazz hand people

38:55.028 --> 38:56.334
to donate their skills--

38:56.377 --> 38:57.639
- Yeah, but I didn't ask them
to donate--

38:57.683 --> 38:59.989
- I mean, they'd donate
anything for you.

39:00.033 --> 39:02.252
So now they're donating
what you really need

39:02.296 --> 39:04.559
and called a few friends.

39:04.603 --> 39:05.908
- Well, that's amazing.

39:08.041 --> 39:09.129
You're hired.

39:09.172 --> 39:10.348
- Oh! Oh...
- Full-time.

39:10.391 --> 39:13.394
- Oh, goddess, help me.

39:13.438 --> 39:15.831
Okay, you can stop that now.

39:15.875 --> 39:17.006
- Come on, bring it in.
- Okay.

39:17.050 --> 39:18.051
- We did it.
- Wow.

39:18.094 --> 39:20.140
- We did it.
- Yep, we did.

39:20.183 --> 39:21.359
That's good.
- Sorry about that.

39:21.402 --> 39:22.490
- Okay, nope.
- Got excited.

39:22.534 --> 39:24.057
- Human touch, wow.
- Okay.

39:24.100 --> 39:27.016
[soft a cappella music]

39:27.060 --> 39:31.238
♪

39:31.281 --> 39:35.024
- ♪ Beautiful dreamer

39:35.068 --> 39:38.985
♪ Wake unto me

39:39.028 --> 39:41.204
♪ Starlight and dewdrops

39:41.248 --> 39:45.034
♪ Are waiting for thee

39:45.078 --> 39:47.123
- [sighs]

39:47.167 --> 39:50.083
- ♪ Sounds of the rude world

39:50.126 --> 39:54.174
♪ Heard in the day

39:54.217 --> 39:55.654
- You know,
there's really no reason

39:55.697 --> 39:58.047
things should be awkward
between us.

39:58.091 --> 39:59.266
- I know.

39:59.309 --> 40:00.746
That'd be silly.

40:02.574 --> 40:03.488
- I haven't tried that yet.

40:03.531 --> 40:04.663
That's good, right?

40:04.706 --> 40:06.229
Okay, I'll do this one then.

40:06.273 --> 40:07.448
Thank you.

40:08.493 --> 40:11.191
- Why didn't you tell me?

40:11.234 --> 40:12.845
- Didn't realize
I was supposed to.

40:12.888 --> 40:14.412
- [laughs]

40:14.455 --> 40:16.631
No, you don't have to--

40:16.675 --> 40:17.893
you're not supposed to tell me.

40:17.937 --> 40:19.286
I just kinda thought
you might want to.

40:19.329 --> 40:21.114
- I see.

40:21.157 --> 40:25.161
So you tell me everything.

40:25.205 --> 40:27.337
There's no secrets between us.

40:30.079 --> 40:32.691
- Well...
- Yeah, I knew it.

40:32.734 --> 40:33.822
- You don't know what I was
gonna say.

40:33.866 --> 40:35.215
- Oh, I know what you were
gonna say.

40:35.258 --> 40:36.782
- I highly doubt that.

40:39.306 --> 40:41.569
- You were seeing someone
last year.

40:42.875 --> 40:44.572
- Yeah.

40:44.616 --> 40:46.574
That's exactly what
I was gonna say.

40:49.229 --> 40:50.448
How'd you know that?

40:52.232 --> 40:54.016
- Why didn't you tell me?

40:56.976 --> 40:58.934
- I didn't tell anyone.

40:58.978 --> 41:00.719
- Why?

41:00.762 --> 41:04.287
- Because--

41:04.331 --> 41:06.376
be--I don't know.

41:11.164 --> 41:13.514
It was--

41:13.558 --> 41:16.604
it was fragile,
and I just thought...

41:16.648 --> 41:19.564
that I should protect...

41:22.871 --> 41:24.612
- Protect what?

41:24.656 --> 41:28.007
- ♪ Beautiful dreamer

41:28.050 --> 41:29.182
♪ Beam on my heart

41:29.225 --> 41:31.358
- Excuse me.

41:31.401 --> 41:32.968
M'lady.

41:33.012 --> 41:34.840
May I have this dance?

41:34.883 --> 41:37.495
- I would be delighted,
kind sir.

41:37.538 --> 41:39.497
[both laugh]
Excuse me.

41:39.540 --> 41:42.021
- ♪ Then will all clouds

41:42.064 --> 41:46.504
♪ Of sorrow depart

41:46.547 --> 41:48.636
♪ Beautiful dreamer

41:48.680 --> 41:52.248
♪ Awake unto me

41:52.292 --> 41:53.902
- [laughs]

41:53.946 --> 41:59.212
- ♪ Beautiful dreamer, awake

41:59.255 --> 42:00.866
♪ Unto me

42:00.909 --> 42:02.128
- [squeals]

42:02.171 --> 42:05.087
[laughing]

42:06.698 --> 42:13.748
- ♪ Unto me
